Sometimes we just think we're bored when we have difficulty concentrating.
Professor Eastwood and colleagues pointed to an ancient experiment in September in which participants listened to a recording of a person reading a journal article in their study "Unbusy Mind: Describing Boring in terms of Interest" published in the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science.
Some groups heard a loud and unrelated television show in the next room, others heard it as being very little noticeable at a very low level, but the third group never heard the sound.
Those who heard of low-level television reported more bored than the other two groups, had difficulty concentrating but were not sure why, and associated this difficulty with distress.
